## Day 1 — Web Fundamentals (Client–Server, HTTP)

🟢 **Beginner:** The web is a conversation between two computers. Your browser (the **client**) asks for something; a **server** somewhere answers. The language they speak is **HTTP** — a set of polite request/response rules. When you open Zero Hunger, your browser sends an HTTP request ("give me the home page"), the server replies with HTML/CSS/JS, and the browser paints it on screen. A **database** sits behind the server, storing the actual donation records.

🔵 **Advanced:** HTTP is a *stateless* text protocol over TCP. Each request carries a **method** (GET, POST, PUT, DELETE), **headers** (metadata like `Content-Type`, `Authorization`), and optionally a **body**. The server replies with a **status code** (2xx success, 3xx redirect, 4xx client error, 5xx server error) and its own headers/body. Statelessness is *why* we later need tokens (JWT) — the server doesn't "remember" you between requests. Understanding the three-tier architecture (browser → API server → database) now will make every later week click into place: React lives in tier 1, Express/Node in tier 2, MongoDB in tier 3.

📖 **Read:**
