## Day 3 — Authentication (JWT), Login/Register APIs

🟢 **Beginner:** **Authentication** answers "who are you?" Users **register** (create an account) and **log in** (prove it). A **JWT** (JSON Web Token) is a signed ID card the server gives you on login; you attach it to future requests so the server knows it's really you — without storing a session.

🔵 **Advanced:** **Never store plain passwords** — hash them with `bcrypt` (salted, slow by design). On login, compare the hash; if valid, sign a JWT with a secret and an expiry. The client sends it as `Authorization: Bearer <token>`; an auth **middleware** verifies the signature and attaches `req.user`. This is where Week 1's *statelessness* pays off — the token *is* the state. Layer **role-based access control (RBAC)**: encode the role (Admin / NGO / Vendor / Donor / Volunteer) in the token and gate routes with a `requireRole()` middleware. Keep secrets in `.env`, use short-lived access tokens, and understand the refresh-token pattern.

📖 **Read:**
- [jwt.io — Introduction to JSON Web Tokens](https://jwt.io/introduction)
- [npm — bcrypt](https://www.npmjs.com/package/bcrypt) · [npm — jsonwebtoken](https://www.npmjs.com/package/jsonwebtoken)
- [Express — Writing middleware](https://expressjs.com/en/guide/writing-middleware.html)
