## Day 1 — DevOps Basics, CI/CD Concepts

🟢 **Beginner:** **DevOps** is the culture and tooling that gets code from your laptop to live users quickly and safely. **CI/CD** = **Continuous Integration** (automatically test/build every change) + **Continuous Delivery/Deployment** (automatically ship it).

🔵 **Advanced:** CI catches breakage early by running install → lint → test → build on every push, against a shared `main`. CD then promotes passing builds toward production (with optional manual approval). Core principles: automate everything, keep builds fast and reproducible, fail loudly, and treat infrastructure/config as versioned code. Know the pipeline stages and the difference between *delivery* (ready to deploy) and *deployment* (auto-live). This mindset is what turns your Week 4 app into a reliably shippable product.

📖 **Read:**
- [TutorialsPoint — DevOps Tutorial](https://www.tutorialspoint.com/devops/index.htm)
- [Atlassian — What is CI/CD?](https://www.atlassian.com/continuous-delivery/principles/continuous-integration-vs-delivery-vs-deployment)
- [GitHub — Understanding GitHub Actions](https://docs.github.com/en/actions/learn-github-actions/understanding-github-actions)
- [Red Hat — What is DevOps?](https://www.redhat.com/en/topics/devops)

🛠️ **Practice:** Write down the ideal pipeline for Zero Hunger as a list of stages (checkout → install → lint → test → build → deploy). Identify which steps protect `main` from broken code.

