## Day 2 — GitHub Actions (Automation), Build Pipeline

🟢 **Beginner:** **GitHub Actions** runs your CI/CD automatically inside GitHub. You write a small YAML file describing steps; GitHub runs them on every push or pull request.

🔵 **Advanced:** A **workflow** (`.github/workflows/ci.yml`) defines **triggers** (`on: push`/`pull_request`), **jobs** (run on a fresh runner), and **steps** (actions or shell commands). Use the official `checkout` and `setup-node` actions, cache dependencies for speed, run tests, and build both frontend and backend. Store credentials in **encrypted secrets**, use matrix builds to test multiple Node versions, and add a status badge to your README. Gate merges on green checks — this is real-world team hygiene the trainers will look for.

📖 **Read:**
- [GitHub — Actions quickstart](https://docs.github.com/en/actions/quickstart)
- [GitHub — Workflow syntax for GitHub Actions](https://docs.github.com/en/actions/using-workflows/workflow-syntax-for-github-actions)
- [GitHub — Building & testing Node.js](https://docs.github.com/en/actions/automating-builds-and-tests/building-and-testing-nodejs)
- [GitHub — Encrypted secrets](https://docs.github.com/en/actions/security-guides/encrypted-secrets)

🛠️ **Practice:** Add `.github/workflows/ci.yml` that, on every push, checks out the code, installs dependencies, and runs the build for both frontend and backend. Make a PR and watch the checks run.

